## **How to Follow Up Student Progress**

As a mentor in the **WordPress Credits** program, one of your key responsibilities is to help students stay on track and make steady progress throughout their journey. This involves regular communication, structured check-ins, and a clear understanding of how students move through the course.

1. ## **Weekly Meetings**

In these meetings you will: 

* Review progress made during the week  
* Discuss blockers or questions  
* Set goals for the following week  
* Offer feedback and encouragement  
* Keep students motivated and accountable

Some requirements: 

* You are expected to meet with your students **once a week**.   
* It’s a good practice to keep these meetings **consistent** (same day and time each week).  
* The recommended length for meeting each student is 30 minutes/week, but it can change depending on the case.   
* If you have several students using the same language, you can set a group meeting to keep track of all of them at once and even encourage the collaboration between them. 

2. ## **Asynchronous Communication**

Between meetings, stay connected through **Slack, email, or another agreed-upon tool**.

Students are expected to reply in **24 hours during working days**, receipt of a message and provide a timeframe for a more detailed reply. We expect you to reply to them in the same time window. 

To be proactive, encourage your student to:

* Share updates or drafts mid-week  
* Ask questions as soon as they arise  
* Use asynchronous channels for small clarifications or check-ins

3. ## **Tracking Progress through Airtable**

Each student’s reply to the blue buttons in the course is documented through an **Airtable dashboard**. As a mentor, we will give you access to a pre-filtered dashboard with all your students' replies. 

We will send you the URL once you have been activated as a WordPress Credits Mentor. 

Please, **review these entries before your weekly meetings**, so you can value their progress and help them move forward during the meeting. 

Important information to check on the student report dashboard: 

* Remind them to submit every form using always **the same email** they used when applied to the program  
* Make sure their **project and website is correctly aligned** with the objective of the course: **contribution to WordPress**  
* Make sure the posts they publish and submit are updates and reflections on their contribution work  
* If any of their replies does not fit with the purpose of the course, please ask them to modify and **resubmit the specific form**

4. ## **Deals Selection for Creating Personal Website**

When the student reaches the ‘Create your personal website’ lesson, they will ask you about the promotion code for one hosting deal and/or several plugins discount codes, listed in that page. 

We will provide you with the list of codes. If your student is already asking this and we haven’t shared it with you, please let us know. 

5. ## **Encouragement and Guidance**

As a mentor, part of your role is to help students find the right people and communities within WordPress.

If a student wants to contribute to an area outside your own expertise, guide them toward the **appropriate team or contributor network**. You can do this by:

* Introducing them to active contributors in the relevant **WordPress Slack channels**.  
* Encouraging them to attend that team’s **weekly meeting** to ask questions and learn how the group works.  
* Sharing **team handbooks or documentation links** that explain contribution processes and communication norms.  
* Helping them craft a short introduction message when reaching out to new contributors or teams.  
* If you personally know someone experienced in that area, **connect the student directly** with that contributor. A personal introduction can make it easier for the student to integrate into the team and receive more specific guidance.

Facilitating these connections not only helps students advance their projects, but also teaches them how to **navigate the open-source ecosystem independently**, a key outcome of the WordPress Credits experience.

6. ## **Biweekly Reports via Slack**

Mentors are expected to share a short update every two weeks in the private Slack channel **\#wpcredits-private** (you will be invited when activated as a mentor). 

This channel is your space to:

* Report on your students’ progress and engagement  
* Share any doubts, challenges, or observations about their projects  
* Ask for advice from other mentors or program administrators

Every two weeks, an automated message in the channel will remind you to post your report. Your update doesn’t need to be long — a few lines summarizing each student’s situation is enough.

Example:

*Student A: progressing well, published two reflection posts these weeks. Student B: struggling with time management, we agreed on smaller milestones. Overall, both on track.*

These reports help the admin team keep track of how students and mentors are doing across the program and allow for early intervention if support is needed.

If you encounter any issue that requires immediate attention, don’t wait for the biweekly report — you can always reach out through **\#wpcredits-private** at any time.

## **Mentor Checklist (Suggested Routine)**

- [ ]  Review your student’s Airtable updates weekly  
- [ ]  Conduct a consistent weekly meeting (video or audio call)  
- [ ]  Follow up mid-week with a short message  
- [ ]  Log key notes or action points from each meeting  
- [ ]  Provide feedback and redirect when needed  
- [ ]  Report to the \#wpcredits-private channel biweekly or whenever you need help  
- [ ]  Celebrate milestones and visible progress

By maintaining regular, structured follow-up, you help students feel supported and confident — while also ensuring their work aligns with the goals of both the program and the WordPress community.
